<div id="review_2703064279" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2703064279" />
    <a title="Meagan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10673633-meagan"><img alt="Meagan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553710088p2/10673633.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2703064279?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Meagan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Meagan" href="/user/show/10673633-meagan">Meagan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10673633-meagan?shelf=family">family</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10673633-meagan?shelf=black-authors">black-authors</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10673633-meagan?shelf=authors-of-color">authors-of-color</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2703064279" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6836454313665408490">The clever humor of this coming-of-age story is only eclipsed by its deft handling of race for a biracial eight year old who doesn’t yet know he’s not white in rural 1960s Georgia. The suspense of the story hangs on Huey’s own innocence and our desire for him to learn the truth warring with our need to protect him from it. Masterfully executed. I certainly went into this book thinking it was just another “tragic mulatto” story but it had more heft than that, particularly because our main charact</span>
  <span id="freeText6836454313665408490" style="display:none">The clever humor of this coming-of-age story is only eclipsed by its deft handling of race for a biracial eight year old who doesn’t yet know he’s not white in rural 1960s Georgia. The suspense of the story hangs on Huey’s own innocence and our desire for him to learn the truth warring with our need to protect him from it. Masterfully executed. I certainly went into this book thinking it was just another “tragic mulatto” story but it had more heft than that, particularly because our main characters aren’t always that sympathetic. I want to return to this book again one day just to study the way the author used Huey’s childishness and naïveté as a real function of the story. Thoroughly impressed. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6836454313665408490" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


